[1
Date: 7 Nov 2000 16:09:16 +1100
From: John Walker <johnw@icpmr.wsahs.nsw.gov.au>

A case of trypanosomiasis infected in Serengeti diagnosed in Sydney
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
In January 1998 a 30 year old Australian woman visited the Serengeti park
for several days before returning to Sydney. She became ill 24 hours after
her return, with fever, rigors and headache. Initial examination of blood
films for malaria revealed nothing but, when the illness persisted for 3
days she was referred to this hospital where numerous trypanosomes were
found. She was initially treated with pentamidine and, when it became
available, suramin. She made a full recovery.
This was the first case of African trypanosomiasis seen in Australia for 50
years, the only other known infection having been acquired in West Africa
during WWII.
--
John Walker, PhD
Director, Department of Parasitology
